1 (i) "Veterinarian" means an individual who holds a valid license to practice veterinary medicine
2 under 37-18-305 or a similar state law in the jurisdiction in which the veterinarian practices.
3 (j) "Veterinary expenses" means the costs associated with medical advice, diagnosis, care, or
4 treatment provided by a veterinarian, including but not limited to the cost of drugs prescribed by a veterinarian.
5 (k) "Waiting period" means the period of time specified in a pet insurance policy that is required to
6 transpire before some or all of the coverage in the policy can begin. Waiting periods may not be applied to
7 renewals of existing coverage.
8 (l) "Wellness program" means a subscription or reimbursement-based program that is separate
9 from an insurance policy and that provides goods and services to promote the general health, safety, or
10 wellbeing of the pet. A wellness program otherwise meeting the definition of insurance set forth in 33-1-201 is
11 still subject to Title 33. This definition is not intended to classify a contract directly between a service provider
12 and a pet owner that only involves the two parties as being insurance unless other indicia of an insurance
13 contract also exist.
14
15 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Disclosures. (1) Before completing the sale of a pet insurance policy, a
16 pet insurer transacting in pet insurance shall disclose the following to consumers:
17 (a) if the policy excludes coverage due to any of the following:
18 (i) a preexisting condition;
19 (ii) a hereditary disorder;
20 (iii) a congenital anomaly or disorder; or
21 (iv) a chronic condition;
22 (b) if the policy includes any other exclusions, the following statement: "Other exclusions may
23 apply. Please refer to the exclusions section of the policy for more information."
24 (c) any policy provision that limits coverage through a waiting period or affiliation period, a
25 deductible, coinsurance, or an annual or lifetime policy limit;
26 (d) whether the pet insurer reduces coverage or increases premiums based on the insured's claim
27 history, the age of the covered pet or a change in the geographic location of the insured; and
28 (e) if the underwriting company differs from the brand name used to market and sell the product.
