1 (2) As provided in this subsection (2), an insured has the right to examine and return the policy.
2 (a) Unless the insured has filed a claim under the pet insurance policy, pet insurance applicants
3 have the right to examine and return the policy, certificate or rider to the company or an insurance producer of
4 the company within 15 days of its receipt and to have the premium refunded if, after examination of the policy,
5 certificate or rider, the applicant is not satisfied for any reason.
6 (b) Pet insurance policies, certificates, and riders must have a notice prominently printed on the
7 first page or attached to the first page including specific instructions to accomplish a return. The following free
8 look statement or language that is substantially similar must be included:
9 "You have 15 days from the day you receive this policy, certificate, or rider to review it and
10 return it to the company if you decide not to keep it. You do not have to tell the company why you are returning
11 it. If you decide not to keep it, simply return it to the company at its administrative office or to the
12 agent/insurance producer that you bought it from, so long as you have not filed a claim. You must return it
13 within 15 days of the day you first received it. The company will refund the full amount of any premium paid
14 within 30 days after it receives the returned policy, certificate, or rider. The premium refund will be sent directly
15 to the person who paid it. The policy, certificate, or rider will be void as if it had never been issued."
16 (3) A pet insurer shall clearly disclose a summary description of the basis or formula on which the
17 pet insurer determines claim payments under a pet insurance policy within the policy, prior to policy issuance.
18 (4) A pet insurer that uses a benefit schedule to determine claim payment under a pet insurance
19 policy shall clearly disclose the applicable benefit schedule in the policy.
20 (5) A pet insurer that determines claim payments under a pet insurance policy based on usual and
21 customary fees, or any other reimbursement limitation based on prevailing veterinary service provider charges,
22 shall include a usual and customary fee limitation provision in the policy that clearly describes the pet insurer's
23 basis for determining usual and customary fees and how that basis is applied in calculating claim payments.
24 (6) If a medical examination by a licensed veterinarian is required to effectuate coverage, the pet
25 insurer shall clearly and conspicuously disclose the required aspects of the examination prior to purchase and
26 disclose that examination documentation may result in a preexisting condition exclusion.
27 (7) Waiting periods and the requirements applicable to them must be clearly and prominently
28 disclosed to consumers prior to the policy purchase.
